n":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Comps","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Candido, Jorge, Juan, Manuel, Mario, Ricardo, Carolina, Enrique, Fidel, Juan Carlos, Luis.","Catalan and southern French: topographic name from <i>camps</i> ‘fields’, or a habitational name from a place called with this word.","English: habitational name from Castle Camps or Shudy Camps (Cambridgeshire), or from Camps in Nazeing (Essex)."],"variants":[{"name":"Camp","meanings":["Dutch (also <b>Van de Camp</b>) and North German: from <i>camp</i> ‘enclosed, fenced, or hedged piece of land, field’, from Latin <i>campus</i> ‘plain’, hence a topographic name for someone who lived by such a field. Compare   Kamp  .","English: from Middle English <i>kempe</i> ‘warrior’; see   Kemp  . The spelling <i>Camp</i> may be due to the influence of Old English <i>camp</i> ‘battle’ and <i>campian</i> ‘to fight’, or of Old French <i>campion</i> ‘warrior, champion’.","French: mainly southern form of   Champ  ."]}]},{"name":"Adélaïde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic origin (via French  <b>Adélaïde</b> ), from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>heid</i> ‘kind, sort’. It was borne in the 10